00:43:26,488 --> 00:43:27,870
Scott: People need to understand this.

689
00:43:28,691 --> 00:43:34,360
Scott: All solo ortho games are actually just puzzles, right?

690
00:43:35,140 --> 00:43:39,546
Scott: It's sitting there with a Sudoku and trying to find the answer to the Sudoku.

691
00:43:40,247 --> 00:43:47,936
Scott: is the only difference between that and say, playing pandemic by yourself?

692
00:43:47,956 --> 00:43:51,140
Scott: is that pandemic has hidden information in it, right?

693
00:43:51,240 --> 00:43:54,265
Scott: So you don't, it's not just like an automatically solved puzzle?

694
00:43:54,385 --> 00:44:02,960
Rym: Arguably no single player game can be by definition an ortho game because you must be able to rank the players.

695
00:44:04,081 --> 00:44:06,989
Scott: You're ranking yourself as either win or lose the game.

696
00:44:07,350 --> 00:44:08,874
Scott: The opponent doesn't get a rank.

697
00:44:08,934 --> 00:44:10,619
Scott: You rank yourself either yes or no.

698
00:44:10,659 --> 00:44:11,040
Rym: It's a pass.

699
00:44:11,100 --> 00:44:14,712
Rym: Yeah, but ortho games don't say against, they literally say rank the players.

700
00:44:14,772 --> 00:44:17,280
Rym: So the player one always has the same rank.

701
00:44:17,320 --> 00:44:22,008
Scott: Regardless of whether it's an ortho game or not, all solo games are puzzles.

702
00:44:22,089 --> 00:44:28,380
Scott: Doing the crossword puzzle is effectively the same as playing one favorite board game's solo mode.

703
00:44:28,580 --> 00:44:31,465
Rym: Yeah, playing like the one player variant is increasingly popular.

704
00:44:32,466 --> 00:44:41,820
Rym: I think our point would stand that a board game that says one plus players, the one player version is just a different game that uses the same components.

705
00:44:43,321 --> 00:44:49,880
Scott: Yeah, it's like you can play, you know, what's a good example of something here?

706
00:44:50,441 --> 00:44:55,051
Rym: I mean all the interesting one player game examples I have are not really ortho games.

707
00:44:55,091 --> 00:44:57,075
Rym: Like Hades, it's an experience.

708
00:44:57,156 --> 00:44:59,040
Rym: It's an interactive entertainment for one.

709
00:45:00,421 --> 00:45:05,400
Rym: I wouldn't even consider Hades to be an ortho game because you're not ranking players against each other.

710
00:45:05,900 --> 00:45:06,940
Scott: Right, well consider this.

711
00:45:07,320 --> 00:45:09,605
Rym: And winning this is a variable scale.

712
00:45:09,866 --> 00:45:10,728
Rym: Did you beat the game?

