00:45:14,016 --> 00:45:15,900
Rym: It's almost not even a relevant conversation.

717
00:45:16,721 --> 00:45:19,205
Scott: Right, well you have chess, which is a two player game normally.

718
00:45:20,207 --> 00:45:23,112
Scott: But one player chess would be chess puzzles, literally.

719
00:45:23,933 --> 00:45:28,040
Scott: You're using the same pieces as chess and the same rules as chess.

720
00:45:28,520 --> 00:45:35,540
Scott: And being good at one player chess puzzles might help you get better at two player chess.

721
00:45:35,660 --> 00:45:36,200
Rym: That's a good point.

722
00:45:36,240 --> 00:45:53,420
Scott: But playing one player chess, just here's a board, you know, find the checkmate or whatever, right, in one move, you know, that puzzle, is that activity in and of itself is an entirely different game from two player chess.

723
00:45:53,560 --> 00:46:01,460
Scott: Although it shares many, you know, similar rules within it, a puzzle is not the same thing as playing against another person.

724
00:46:01,500 --> 00:46:08,070
Scott: There are two different categories, right, so that's just how it is.

725
00:46:08,591 --> 00:46:14,380
Scott: So when people are out there saying like, "Oh, I want a solo mode for this game," right, say you're playing Ticket to Ride.

726
00:46:14,600 --> 00:46:17,719
Rym: Yeah, what you're saying is, "I want a different game that uses the same

727
00:46:17,739 --> 00:46:17,940
Rym: components.".

728
00:46:17,940 --> 00:46:19,888
Scott: Yeah, I want a different game, exactly.

729
00:46:19,969 --> 00:46:22,600
Scott: And it's fundamentally not the same thing.

730
00:46:23,484 --> 00:46:24,700
Scott: It's a different activity.

731
00:46:25,200 --> 00:46:34,180
Rym: Even more interesting, some tabletop games add like mechanical AIs that will serve the role of a player and follow rules.

732
00:46:34,640 --> 00:46:39,680
Rym: But even then, those things act in a way that is not the same as a real player in most cases.

733
00:46:40,041 --> 00:46:44,394
Rym: And if it is the same as a real player, it's just a very simplistic human opponent.

734
00:46:44,474 --> 00:46:46,500
Rym: It's really a two player game and one of them is an AI.

735
00:46:47,222 --> 00:46:47,322
Scott: Right.

736
00:46:47,342 --> 00:46:50,069
Scott: Well, that goes back to what I was saying about one player pandemic, right?

737
00:46:50,109 --> 00:46:54,600
Scott: The difference being is like, yeah, there's two kinds of one player puzzles.

738
00:46:54,860 --> 00:46:57,632
Scott: There's ones with perfect information and ones without perfect.

739
00:46:57,672 --> 00:46:59,379
Scott: I mean, there's more categories than that.

740
00:46:59,880 --> 00:47:13,700
Scott: But the biggest difference is the puzzles that are perfect information, like a Sudoku, and the puzzles with the hidden information, like, you know, pandemic by yourself, because there's a deck of cards that's face down.

741
00:47:13,780 --> 00:47:17,794
Scott: You don't know what order they're in, or you might not even know the contents of that deck, right?

742
00:47:17,915 --> 00:47:19,440
Scott: So that would be even more hidden information.

743
00:47:20,480 --> 00:47:26,431
Scott: And the way you approach those puzzles is completely different, you know, but procedurally.

744
00:47:26,912 --> 00:47:31,680
Scott: So if you like one kind of puzzle, you might not like the other kind, but they are still both puzzles.

745
00:47:32,301 --> 00:47:36,940
Scott: It's a puzzle solving exercise, not a gaming, ortho gaming exercise either way.

746
00:47:37,220 --> 00:47:47,120
Rym: Two player is honestly the most interesting space to me because two player games or two team games or races, we'll get into that.

747
00:47:47,520 --> 00:47:50,364
Scott: Yeah, when we say players, we mean sides, right?

748
00:47:50,384 --> 00:48:00,780
Scott: So even if there are like, you know, if you and all of your friends gather around a table and on the table is Klondike Solitaire, and you're all trying to play Klondike together, right?

749
00:48:00,920 --> 00:48:02,689
Scott: Like, oh, you're trying to help spot the right move.

750
00:48:02,990 --> 00:48:04,337
Scott: That's still a one player game.

751
00:48:04,357 --> 00:48:05,040
Scott: That's still a puzzle.

752
00:48:05,140 --> 00:48:08,590
Rym: That's why code games can take N players.

753
00:48:08,870 --> 00:48:10,655
Rym: Like how many people can you fit around that table?

754
00:48:10,715 --> 00:48:12,320
Rym: Because there's two teams.

755
00:48:13,340 --> 00:48:13,962
Scott: Yeah.

756
00:48:14,182 --> 00:48:15,807
Scott: Or, you know, you can ask for help.

757
00:48:15,887 --> 00:48:20,660
Scott: You know, your whole family can sit around a crossword puzzle and try to solve it together or a word search, right?

758
00:48:21,680 --> 00:48:24,085
Scott: Or just playing pandemic by the rules.

759
00:48:24,185 --> 00:48:25,127
Scott: Is that a co-op game?

760
00:48:25,267 --> 00:48:27,591
Scott: No, that's a one player game pandemic, right?

761
00:48:27,912 --> 00:48:32,260
Scott: And many co-op games are one player games in disguise, right?

762
00:48:32,681 --> 00:48:36,069
Scott: They say they're co-op, but actually they're just puzzles hidden information.

763
00:48:36,751 --> 00:48:40,300
Scott: Some of them have a trainer mechanic thing, which makes them slightly different.

764
00:48:40,982 --> 00:48:44,120
Rym: I almost said bad in most cases, but we've talked about that before.

765
00:48:45,040 --> 00:48:49,710
Scott: And that's why you get the phenomenon known as quarterbacking because you're playing a puzzle.

766
00:48:49,791 --> 00:48:54,160
Scott: And obviously if you're solving a puzzle, whoever is the best at solving a puzzle, right?

767
00:48:54,200 --> 00:48:57,748
Scott: The person who knows the most trivia is going to do the most work on the crossword puzzle.

768
00:48:58,008 --> 00:49:03,260
Scott: And the other is someone, if a child is there who doesn't know a lot of stuff, they're not going to be able to help that much.

769
00:49:03,460 --> 00:49:11,898
Scott: So if you're playing pandemic, which is effectively the same exact activity as five people working on a crossword puzzle together, then it's, it doesn't matter.

770
00:49:11,938 --> 00:49:13,060
Scott: It's not the rules fault.

771
00:49:13,441 --> 00:49:14,663
Scott: It's not the player's fault.

772
00:49:14,703 --> 00:49:18,669
Scott: Stop blaming the other people for the fact that the game has a quarterbacking problem.

773
00:49:18,930 --> 00:49:24,860
Scott: The game's fault is that it's a one player puzzle trying to pass itself off as a co-op activity.

774
00:49:25,840 --> 00:49:33,460
Scott: Co-op, you know, the, the quarterbacking thing is only natural, just like it would be natural with a crossword puzzle because the same activity, right?

775
00:49:33,741 --> 00:49:40,096
Scott: But if you play Hanabi, right, which we've talked about a lot, that's not a single player puzzle, right?

776
00:49:40,136 --> 00:49:41,620
Scott: That's actually a multiplayer game.

777
00:49:43,240 --> 00:49:46,019
Rym: So also Hanabi doesn't really work with two players.

778
00:49:47,220 --> 00:49:47,798
Scott: No, not at all.

779
00:49:48,160 --> 00:49:48,921
Rym: Yep.

780
00:49:48,962 --> 00:49:59,280
Rym: So two player games are so unique and interesting that we did an entire podcast about two player games in 2019 specifically, which I'll link to.

781
00:49:59,400 --> 00:50:01,605
Scott: Two player game is the purest form of game, right?

782
00:50:01,725 --> 00:50:07,116
Scott: If you, it's not a puzzle, you're actually competing against another human being or human beings, right?

783
00:50:07,477 --> 00:50:08,540
Scott: If it's teams or something.

784
00:50:09,900 --> 00:50:16,600
Scott: But unlike the three plus player games that we're going to talk about next, there's no politics and there's no vote who wins.

785
00:50:17,281 --> 00:50:21,431
Rym: I can't like sabotage Scott to let Joey Jojo win.

786
00:50:21,451 --> 00:50:22,273
Rym: There's only Scott.

787
00:50:22,333 --> 00:50:23,997
Rym: I'm always trying to sabotage Scott.

788
00:50:24,017 --> 00:50:25,020
Rym: He's the only person.

789
00:50:25,340 --> 00:50:26,864
Scott: It's two people, right?

790
00:50:26,924 --> 00:50:27,666
Scott: Two sides.

791
00:50:27,947 --> 00:50:30,334
Scott: And each side says, I'm trying to make me win.

792
00:50:30,374 --> 00:50:32,460
Scott: And the other side says, well, I'm trying to make me win.

793
00:50:32,820 --> 00:50:51,220
Scott: And you just test your skills at whatever the game is, whatever skill the game is testing, whether that's fighting in a boxing ring or, you know, running fast or, you know, being good at math or being good at memory or being good with your fingers in a fighting game or being good with your fingers in an RTS.

794
00:50:52,261 --> 00:50:55,407
Rym: There's no possibility of king making.

795
00:50:55,627 --> 00:51:00,596
Rym: There's no possibility of a poor player making a weird move that like messes you up.

796
00:51:00,896 --> 00:51:03,180
Rym: You're just you're playing against one entity.

797
00:51:03,961 --> 00:51:12,440
Scott: Yeah, it's, you know, there could be luck involved, but other than luck that could be in there, it's who, which of the two sides is best, right?

798
00:51:12,500 --> 00:51:13,743
Scott: It's a you're measuring.

799
00:51:13,943 --> 00:51:22,380
Scott: It's a true measurement, as true as you're going to have of who of the two sides in the game was better and or luckier at that thing.

800
00:51:23,142 --> 00:51:26,720
Scott: At this moment, you get and you get an answer unless there was cheating or something.

801
00:51:26,920 --> 00:51:28,542
Rym: These are some of the asterisk.

802
00:51:28,602 --> 00:51:34,430
Rym: These are some of the only games that can have what I would consider formal matchmaking.

803
00:51:34,811 --> 00:51:41,740
Rym: that is guaranteed over time with a sufficient quantity of players to accurately rank the real skill of those players.

804
00:51:42,060 --> 00:51:58,220
Rym: These are also games that can devolve into nothing games, broken or solved games very easily or devolve to the point to where the skill that's being tested in the end between two advanced players is radically different from what is being tested among novice players.

805
00:51:59,061 --> 00:51:59,181
Scott: Yep.

806
00:51:59,522 --> 00:52:08,100
Scott: But yeah, I think the point you made originally is that like, yeah, this is pretty much the only valid category for competitive games, right?

807
00:52:08,200 --> 00:52:16,979
Scott: If you want to have a competitive game where you actually put some sort of value on the winning and losing, you're not just declaring a winner or a loser for fun, right?

808
00:52:17,560 --> 00:52:23,460
Scott: Because you're playing games, you actually want to like award a trophy or a prize prize money, right?

809
00:52:23,721 --> 00:52:32,160
Scott: Or, you know, make someone's entire career based on being good at this game or make important decisions based on the result of the game.

810
00:52:33,022 --> 00:52:34,970
Scott: It has to be a two player competitive game.

811
00:52:35,211 --> 00:52:36,355
Scott: It can't be any other kind.

812
00:52:36,476 --> 00:52:37,520
Scott: It can't be a one player.

813
00:52:37,640 --> 00:52:39,988
Scott: It can't be like you solve the puzzle, right?

814
00:52:40,028 --> 00:52:41,172
Scott: It's like, what?

815
00:52:41,373 --> 00:52:42,396
Scott: Who cares, right?

816
00:52:42,416 --> 00:52:43,520
Scott: Many people solve the puzzle.

817
00:52:43,841 --> 00:52:48,373
Scott: But as soon as you say, oh, well, see, I have two people and see who solved the puzzle faster.

818
00:52:48,393 --> 00:52:50,940
Scott: Oh, well, now we got something, right?

819
00:52:51,522 --> 00:52:53,434
Scott: It's no longer can you solve it.

820
00:52:53,515 --> 00:52:54,300
Scott: It's who is faster.

821
00:52:54,520 --> 00:53:01,260
Rym: Now, an interesting sidebar, all games that are non interactive, meaning players cannot affect each other.

822
00:53:01,561 --> 00:53:06,220
Rym: They're effectively races that are independent, like a 5K run, for example.

823
00:53:06,540 --> 00:53:09,310
Rym: I can't like shove the person in the lane next to me over.

824
00:53:09,330 --> 00:53:12,140
Rym: Yeah, but then they stop the race and I probably go to jail.

825
00:53:13,662 --> 00:53:19,075
Rym: So basically those games, it literally does not matter how many players they are.

826
00:53:19,115 --> 00:53:20,980
Rym: They're the same experience either way.

827
00:53:21,900 --> 00:53:25,300
Scott: But as long as they're not one, if you run a 5K by yourself.

828
00:53:26,481 --> 00:53:30,978
Rym: Yeah, I could compete against myself, I guess, but that's not really previous time.

829
00:53:31,019 --> 00:53:31,340
Rym: Yeah.

830
00:53:32,300 --> 00:53:34,648
Rym: So in fact, you know what we do in the episode.

831
00:53:34,688 --> 00:53:38,120
Rym: we did, I'm going to read the description from it on two player games, because here's what we said.

832
00:53:38,200 --> 00:53:38,943
Rym: It's not on GeekNights.

833
00:53:38,983 --> 00:53:43,760
Rym: We consider the unique nature of two player games in a non solitaire, non race game.

834
00:53:44,221 --> 00:53:48,740
Rym: One, two, three, four plus players are radically different experiences.

835
00:53:49,060 --> 00:53:51,260
Rym: Two player games are in a unique and fascinating space.

836
00:53:51,501 --> 00:53:55,520
Rym: They devolve into chess, tic-tac-toe or rock, paper, scissors in most tabletop games.

837
00:53:55,920 --> 00:53:57,008
Rym: Three player games are political.

838
00:53:57,330 --> 00:53:58,700
Rym: Four player games are basically the same.

839
00:53:58,760 --> 00:54:01,113
Rym: But two, two is a class of its own.

840
00:54:01,153 --> 00:54:02,520
Rym: That's the description for that episode.

841
00:54:02,640 --> 00:54:11,640
Scott: And that's exactly right, because when you have a race, right, you can have any number of players in a race and have it be a valid competition where no one can affect anyone else.

842
00:54:11,820 --> 00:54:14,687
Scott: Everyone is doing a solo activity, right?

843
00:54:14,948 --> 00:54:19,960
Scott: But you're measuring how well everyone did the solo activity against each other.

844
00:54:20,321 --> 00:54:27,380
Scott: So everyone ran fast by themselves and then we'll look and see who ran the fastest and that's the winner, right?

845
00:54:27,640 --> 00:54:29,488
Scott: Everyone will do a Sudoku by themselves.

846
00:54:29,508 --> 00:54:32,360
Scott: Whoever solved it the fastest is the winner, right?

847
00:54:32,701 --> 00:54:34,412
Scott: The number of players there doesn't matter.

848
00:54:35,077 --> 00:54:35,540
Scott: It's a race.

849
00:54:35,960 --> 00:54:41,660
Rym: So imagine a two player race that is interactive, like a foot race where Scott and I are running.

850
00:54:41,720 --> 00:54:49,880
Scott: Two player is the only way that you can avoid having a race and have interaction with the other player.

851
00:54:50,060 --> 00:54:51,971
Scott: You actually interact with the other person.

852
00:54:51,991 --> 00:54:53,420
Scott: You hinder them, they hinder you.

853
00:54:53,800 --> 00:55:02,340
Scott: You are in each other's space doing things to each other, but you've maintained the value of the competition, you know, the purity of the competition.

854
00:55:02,480 --> 00:55:10,860
Rym: So if Scott and I are having a foot race, just the two of us, and it's interactive, if he trips me, well, he wins most likely.

855
00:55:11,921 --> 00:55:18,640
Rym: But in a three player race, if Scott trips me, our slow friend, Joey Jojo is going to win the race, possibly.

856
00:55:19,461 --> 00:55:19,621
Scott: Yep.

857
00:55:19,942 --> 00:55:27,000
Scott: So yeah, the three plus player games, any game that is three or more players, doesn't matter how many, it could be a million.

858
00:55:27,240 --> 00:55:27,901
Scott: It could be two.

859
00:55:28,282 --> 00:55:28,943
Scott: It can't be two.

860
00:55:29,003 --> 00:55:31,126
Scott: It could be four, right?

861
00:55:31,186 --> 00:55:40,820
Scott: Any game with three or more players or sides, if there is any way for the players to interact with each other at all, right?

862
00:55:41,501 --> 00:55:44,629
Scott: Which could be, you know, direct interaction.

863
00:55:44,649 --> 00:55:45,391
Scott: That's obvious.

864
00:55:45,451 --> 00:55:49,320
Scott: Like, oh, you can just play a card that says so and so loses 10 points.

865
00:55:49,460 --> 00:55:49,741
Scott: Yeah.

866
00:55:50,022 --> 00:55:52,689
Scott: Um, you know, but it could be very indirect.

867
00:55:52,749 --> 00:55:56,840
Scott: Like, oh, there's a board with, you know, 10 meeples on it.

868
00:55:57,181 --> 00:56:00,931
Scott: And on your turn, you take a meeple from the everyone's taking from the same board.

869
00:56:01,332 --> 00:56:04,320
Scott: It's like you're barely interacting with each other, but you're still interacting.

870
00:56:04,901 --> 00:56:12,800
Scott: You might choose to take the meeple that helps someone else more than the meeple that helps you the most because it'll hurt them for you to take that meeple.

871
00:56:13,441 --> 00:56:15,483
Scott: And you're sort of indirectly affecting them.

872
00:56:15,523 --> 00:56:29,360
Scott: If there's any shared resource, any way for the players actions to have any effect on the other players actions in any way, and there are three or more players, you are playing a political game to some extent.

873
00:56:29,521 --> 00:56:31,328
Scott: Some games are more political than others.

874
00:56:31,810 --> 00:56:34,420
Scott: Some games are nothing but political, like diplomacy.

875
00:56:34,940 --> 00:56:51,260
Rym: But in the end, if you play a three plus player game of any kind, it will either devolve into a perfectly solved solution where if everyone plays equally, you can predict the winner from the beginning, or it will literally just come down to the politics of the interactions.

876
00:56:51,640 --> 00:56:56,680
Rym: Meaning, well, I hurt Scott a little bit and heared me a little bit, so someone else wins.

877
00:56:57,641 --> 00:56:57,781
Scott: Yep.

878
00:56:57,861 --> 00:57:17,480
Scott: Now there are cases where the interaction amount, like the amount you can interact is limited by the rules and skill does matter such that someone who is very good can still just win, even if everyone else is trying to gang up on them intentionally, just because they're that much better than the other players.

879
00:57:18,581 --> 00:57:21,845
Scott: A good example might be something like PUBG, right?

880
00:57:21,925 --> 00:57:33,620
Scott: If someone's just really good at PUBG, they could probably win and be the chicken dinner against 99 Scrubs, even if all the Scrubs were just hunting that one person specifically and not shooting each other.

881
00:57:33,720 --> 00:57:42,720
Rym: I have played in Counter-Strike gun games back in the day where everyone knows there's this one motherfucker who is better than everyone else, and everyone tries to gang up on them and it just doesn't matter.

882
00:57:43,661 --> 00:57:45,023
Scott: Yeah, so that is possible.

883
00:57:45,404 --> 00:57:51,693
Rym: But if everyone is maximally skilled, then skill no longer matters for those people.

884
00:57:52,034 --> 00:57:56,260
Rym: Politics is all that matters, unless the game is solvable at that level.

885
00:57:57,240 --> 00:57:57,300
Scott: Yep.

886
00:57:57,901 --> 00:58:03,952
Scott: So all three plus player games have this political element, if there's interaction, whether you like it or not.

887
00:58:04,092 --> 00:58:06,597
Scott: And this is where the board game Reddit.

888
00:58:06,617 --> 00:58:08,560
Scott: people come into play, right?

889
00:58:08,941 --> 00:58:17,494
Scott: You see people and they're playing something that's highly political, like Root or Tigris and Euphrates or something like that, right?

890
00:58:18,155 --> 00:58:21,280
Scott: And they're coming in with their two-player nonsense, right?

891
00:58:21,600 --> 00:58:22,597
Scott: And they're like, "How many players do I

892
00:58:22,618 --> 00:58:22,699
Scott: need?".

893
00:58:22,880 --> 00:58:29,217
Rym: They're mad that Root is unfair, or "My friend made a bad mistake with the birds and now the cats ran away with the game and that sucks.

894
00:58:29,357 --> 00:58:29,758
Rym: I should have

895
00:58:29,778 --> 00:58:29,979
Rym: won.".

896
00:58:30,660 --> 00:58:32,064
Scott: It's like, that is the game.

897
00:58:32,244 --> 00:58:35,873
Scott: At three plus players, that is what the game is supposed to be.

898
00:58:35,953 --> 00:58:37,357
Scott: That's what it's designed to be.

899
00:58:37,417 --> 00:58:38,680
Scott: It's a political game intentionally.

900
00:58:38,800 --> 00:58:45,540
Rym: If you don't like the fact that the interactions of the players determine who wins, you don't like games with more than two players.

901
00:58:46,822 --> 00:58:48,039
Scott: Unless they're just races.

902
00:58:48,390 --> 00:58:48,618
Scott: Yep.

903
00:58:50,942 --> 00:58:52,167
Scott: So they do.

904
00:58:52,267 --> 00:58:55,320
Scott: let you in the rulebook play two-player Root.

905
00:58:55,820 --> 00:58:56,196
Rym: It's not fun.

906
00:58:56,400 --> 00:59:02,045
Scott: That is A, a bad game, in my opinion, and B, a completely different game.

907
00:59:02,466 --> 00:59:10,153
Scott: It is in no way resembles three plus player Root, except in only these surface details of like, "Yeah, these are the actions you can take on the board and

908
00:59:10,173 --> 00:59:10,393
Scott: such.".

909
00:59:18,341 --> 00:59:23,013
Scott: It's just like a resource-gaining game as opposed to a political game.

910
00:59:23,755 --> 00:59:25,840
Scott: What it takes to win at that game is unrelated.

911
00:59:26,700 --> 00:59:28,386
Scott: I don't even know why they offer it.

912
00:59:28,949 --> 00:59:30,836
Scott: It's like two completely different games with the same box.

913
00:59:31,338 --> 00:59:31,900
Scott: Why is it there?

914
00:59:32,120 --> 00:59:39,360
Rym: While I could say, and I think you'd agree, there is no formal difference between three and any number larger than three.

915
00:59:39,861 --> 00:59:42,860
Rym: There's no formal differences between any of those games at this point.

916
00:59:43,642 --> 00:59:51,080
Rym: But there are soft or informal patterns that we've definitely seen with certain player counts.

917
00:59:51,240 --> 01:00:16,220
Rym: For example, four- and five-player games tend to be very similar to each other, but three-player games very commonly have a very specific pattern where two of the players will get ahead, one of the players falls behind, the player who fell behind is effectively eliminated from the game very early, and the game becomes effectively a two-player game, possibly with the spoiler kingmaker just hanging out in the background.

918
01:00:17,181 --> 01:00:18,869
Scott: Yeah, because there's only three players.

919
01:00:18,909 --> 01:00:21,220
Scott: You don't have a lot of political options.

920
01:00:22,641 --> 01:00:36,760
Scott: And therefore, no matter what the game is, if you have a three-player political game, only after the early game, only two people are really just going to have a chance to win, no matter how well you design that game.

921
01:00:37,687 --> 01:00:39,260
Scott: Can I think of any examples?

922
01:00:39,740 --> 01:00:40,382
Rym: Here's an example.

923
01:00:40,482 --> 01:00:47,099
Rym: If Scott plays a board game with the listeners who aren't crazy about games like we are, like a game Scott's good at.

924
01:00:48,160 --> 01:00:50,002
Rym: So it's Scott and two other listeners.

925
01:00:50,944 --> 01:01:04,221
Rym: If they believe that Scott is better than them at games, it is in their best interest to both attack Scott early to make sure he is effectively eliminated to increase their chances of winning to 50%.

926
01:01:04,221 --> 01:01:08,749
Rym: It is almost impossible to avoid that situation in a three-player game mechanically.

927
01:01:09,870 --> 01:01:15,960
Rym: Three-player games that don't have this pattern of interaction and aren't races are shockingly rare.

928
01:01:16,800 --> 01:01:21,680
Scott: I think the only other pattern would be just one person runs away with it.

929
01:01:21,900 --> 01:01:24,440
Rym: Yep, which I have also seen in some three-player games.

930
01:01:24,921 --> 01:01:33,660
Scott: But for three people to all be in with a good chance of winning towards the end of a three-player game is very unlikely.

931
01:01:34,020 --> 01:01:49,760
Rym: Even in high skill, like a three-player Tigris and Euphrates, even with three people who are extremely high skill and possibly even equal in skill to each other, one player is going to, either by chance or by minor politics, be set behind a little bit.

932
01:01:50,201 --> 01:01:55,200
Rym: And there's like this negative inverse snowball once you're off the board where you can't get back on the board.

933
01:01:55,920 --> 01:02:01,958
Scott: Yeah, you might even be playing like an 18xx, which is like, you know, probably one of the best three-player type games on a board.

934
01:02:01,998 --> 01:02:02,700
Scott: that's a pro, right?

935
01:02:02,760 --> 01:02:08,040
Scott: And it's like, you might be getting late in the game and everyone's like money is pretty close, right?

936
01:02:08,120 --> 01:02:15,960
Scott: And it feels like, yeah, this is really close to three players, but really that small difference, whoever, someone is in third place.

937
01:02:16,761 --> 01:02:18,124
Rym: The second to last operating round.

938
01:02:18,184 --> 01:02:19,246
Rym: Oh, I'm only behind by $80.

939
01:02:19,246 --> 01:02:21,129
Rym: The third to last, the next operating round.

940
01:02:21,149 --> 01:02:21,670
Rym: Okay, now I'm behind by $3,000.

941
01:02:21,670 --> 01:02:22,492
Rym: Next operating round.

942
01:02:22,512 --> 01:02:27,540
Rym: Now I'm behind by $6,000.

943
01:02:27,540 --> 01:02:34,770
Scott: It's just, it feels like you have three players who are in the game, which makes, which keeps the fun level up.

944
01:02:35,171 --> 01:02:38,255
Scott: But the reality is that two players ran away with the game.

945
01:02:38,355 --> 01:02:41,700
Scott: You just didn't tell because the numbers didn't separate that.

946
01:02:41,880 --> 01:02:50,540
Rym: I wonder if I just use some sort of logarithmic or pseudo logarithmic function to look at our value in these games instead of the real number, if that would give me a better sense.

947
01:02:51,780 --> 01:02:52,180
Scott: Yeah, probably.

948
01:02:52,503 --> 01:02:52,799
Scott: Probably.

949
01:02:53,160 --> 01:02:54,017
Scott: Depends on which one though.

950
01:02:54,580 --> 01:03:09,300
Rym: So, but one thing I would say is that the problem that causes one player to fall behind or one player to steamroll ahead in three-player games, they're both actually just symptoms of the same underlying problem and it really just depends on the politics at the table.

951
01:03:09,901 --> 01:03:11,644
Rym: One player running ahead usually happens.

952
01:03:11,904 --> 01:03:17,674
Rym: Imagine me and Scott and Joey Jojo Shabbat who are playing a game and Joey Jojo knows that me and Scott are both good at the game.

953
01:03:18,375 --> 01:03:21,320
Rym: Scott and I tend to fuck each other up to the point that Joey Jojo wins.

954
01:03:22,640 --> 01:03:25,365
Scott: Well, yeah, because if you're good, you have no choice.

955
01:03:25,806 --> 01:03:27,810
Scott: You know, one of the other players is also good.

956
01:03:27,830 --> 01:03:29,393
Scott: You have no choice but to attack them.

957
01:03:29,433 --> 01:03:33,100
Scott: But let's say you got a three-player game with three strong players, right?

958
01:03:33,901 --> 01:03:51,397
Scott: You're still going to be looking at the board and since the game has an interactive political element, right, you're going to calculate at some point, whatever the game is, there'll be some action you can take and you'll recognize, say like Carcassonne, taking points away from someone else is

959
01:03:51,758 --> 01:03:51,878
Rym: as

960
01:03:51,978 --> 01:03:53,719
Scott: good as giving points to yourself.

961
01:03:53,900 --> 01:03:54,340
Scott: They're equal.

962
01:03:55,101 --> 01:03:57,666
Scott: So there's going to be a move that you're going to see.

963
01:03:58,167 --> 01:04:00,652
Scott: that will be negative points for someone, right?

964
01:04:00,692 --> 01:04:01,795
Scott: Maybe you block someone.

965
01:04:01,875 --> 01:04:04,540
Scott: Maybe Rym's working on a castle and I block it, right?

966
01:04:05,960 --> 01:04:09,732
Scott: Well, now it's me and the other person are now ahead and Rym is back.

967
01:04:10,073 --> 01:04:10,655
Scott: It's just natural.

968
01:04:10,876 --> 01:04:12,020
Scott: It's just going to happen.

969
01:04:13,065 --> 01:04:16,060
Rym: My specific strategy I've used for decades...

970
01:04:16,941 --> 01:04:17,639
Scott: Pretend you're losing.

971
01:04:18,280 --> 01:04:23,312
Rym: Well, yeah, I do use psychological tricks, but let's assume I'm playing against you where that shit doesn't work.

972
01:04:23,512 --> 01:04:25,878
Rym: Like, people where they can see right through me.

973
01:04:26,379 --> 01:04:26,800
Rym: In that case...

974
01:04:26,800 --> 01:04:27,709
Scott: Rym's like, "Oh, I'm done.

975
01:04:27,910 --> 01:04:28,557
Scott: I can't win this

976
01:04:28,577 --> 01:04:28,758
Scott: now.".

977
01:04:28,920 --> 01:04:29,621
Scott: Ah, fuck this game.

978
01:04:30,042 --> 01:04:33,008
Rym: Ah, look at me winning.

979
01:04:34,090 --> 01:04:36,114
Rym: That works so well against people who don't know me.

980
01:04:36,154 --> 01:04:36,755
Rym: It's kind of funny.

981
01:04:36,995 --> 01:04:39,380
Rym: Anyway, it used to work on all of you, but you figured me out.

982
01:04:40,061 --> 01:04:41,503
Rym: So, say I can't pull that shit.

983
01:04:42,044 --> 01:04:52,820
Rym: Then my strategy is actually, in most 3-player games, I wait until some other player has taken an action that harms a player on the board who is not me.

984
01:04:53,620 --> 01:04:58,067
Rym: Once that happens, I double down on destroying whoever they hurt a little.

985
01:04:59,469 --> 01:05:00,491
Rym: Dog pile on.

986
01:05:00,851 --> 01:05:01,873
Rym: Remember the Omega-Thon?

987
01:05:01,893 --> 01:05:06,660
Rym: They were playing, like, boom blocks and the first player attacked Green just randomly.

988
01:05:07,001 --> 01:05:10,990
Rym: The second player looked around, laughed, and attacked Green.

989
01:05:11,311 --> 01:05:13,376
Rym: The third player was like, "Oh, well, Green goes

990
01:05:13,396 --> 01:05:13,657
Rym: fourth.".

991
01:05:13,677 --> 01:05:15,060
Rym: Attackin' Green!

992
01:05:16,641 --> 01:05:17,843
Rym: So, Green was basically out of the game.

993
01:05:18,224 --> 01:05:20,448
Rym: The first player comes around again, they attack Blue.

994
01:05:21,069 --> 01:05:26,480
Rym: Blue was the second player, so Blue attacked them, and the third player actually won the game as a result.

995
01:05:28,740 --> 01:05:40,640
Scott: So, the thing to remember here is that all 3+ player games that aren't races have a political element and are therefore inherently different from a 2-player game.

996
01:05:40,800 --> 01:05:45,489
Scott: You cannot go into such a game expecting to win because you were the best.

997
01:05:45,549 --> 01:05:50,377
Scott: You could play the best and lose because people might vote for you to lose, and it's a vote-who-wins game.

998
01:05:50,418 --> 01:05:51,680
Scott: That is what the game is.

999
01:05:52,123 --> 01:05:54,280
Scott: If you don't like that, don't play those games.

1000
01:05:54,540 --> 01:06:00,980
Rym: Even better, the skill of being good at a game like that involves trying to manage the politics.

1001
01:06:01,960 --> 01:06:02,519
Scott: Yes, indeed.

1002
01:06:02,960 --> 01:06:03,561
Rym: Like, for real.

1003
01:06:04,102 --> 01:06:05,024
Rym: Best with your friends.

1004
01:06:05,806 --> 01:06:06,808
Rym: Act like you're losing.

1005
01:06:07,089 --> 01:06:07,810
Rym: Psychology.

1006
01:06:08,131 --> 01:06:12,600
Rym: Do things in-game to protect you from politics if that is an option in the particular game you're playing.

1007
01:06:14,121 --> 01:06:21,660
Scott: One final note, because I mentioned PUBG before, is that when N becomes large, nothing fundamentally changes.

1008
01:06:21,940 --> 01:06:39,040
Scott: As Rym said before, the principles mathematically are the same, but there is a soft difference with very large numbers of players, like a PUBG, in that you're only really able to directly interact with people who are near you.

1009
01:06:39,441 --> 01:06:43,500
Scott: You can't interact with everyone in the game.

1010
01:06:44,680 --> 01:06:48,007
Rym: I'm stuck in a firefight with the eight people who landed kind of near me.

1011
01:06:48,288 --> 01:06:50,092
Rym: Meanwhile, Scott's on the other side of the island.

1012
01:06:50,432 --> 01:06:53,940
Rym: It might be all the shitty people are on the other side of the island, and I'm just boned.

1013
01:06:54,080 --> 01:06:54,301
Rym: Right.

1014
01:06:54,882 --> 01:07:02,540
Scott: So, even though it is fundamentally a vote-who-wins game, think about something like Tetris 99 on the Switch, right?

1015
01:07:03,080 --> 01:07:04,785
Scott: Yeah, you are choosing who to attack.

1016
01:07:04,846 --> 01:07:08,918
Scott: There is a vote-who-wins element there that ultimately determines a lot.

1017
01:07:10,561 --> 01:07:12,940
Rym: More players dilutes the effect of politics.

1018
01:07:13,660 --> 01:07:14,021
Scott: Exactly.

1019
01:07:14,041 --> 01:07:17,747
Scott: It dilutes the effect of politics until the latest stages of the game.

1020
01:07:18,328 --> 01:07:25,520
Scott: Therefore, it ends up being not entirely a race, but more, it goes back to being a race, right?

1021
01:07:25,540 --> 01:07:35,780
Scott: It's like, yeah, if you play Tetris 99, at the end of the game, you're going to be left with, usually, most of the time, the people who are the best at Tetris, as if you had a Tetris race.

1022
01:07:36,361 --> 01:07:40,250
Scott: And then, amongst those people, they will have some sort of competition.

1023
01:07:40,291 --> 01:07:44,280
Scott: that is a combination of Tetris skill and politics together.

1024
01:07:44,640 --> 01:07:56,460
Scott: The other thing that happens- The politics are still present in the early game, but they're so weak, because there's so many players, you know, and- You almost have to bring enough skill to the table to be able to play the politics game at the end.

1025
01:07:57,101 --> 01:07:59,926
Scott: Like, if someone sucked at Tetris, they're just really bad at it.

1026
01:08:00,487 --> 01:08:08,740
Scott: Even if all 98 other players voted for that person to win and didn't attack them, they would probably just die on their own, right?

1027
01:08:09,441 --> 01:08:15,349
Scott: And even if someone was amazing at Tetris, and all 98 other players voted to take them out, right?

1028
01:08:15,570 --> 01:08:22,500
Scott: You can't coordinate that kind of attack, but if you could, you still might not take them out unless some of the other 98 players were good enough.

1029
01:08:22,901 --> 01:08:27,540
Scott: Because that player is so good, they'll just be able to clear if the attack isn't strong enough.

1030
01:08:27,840 --> 01:08:34,033
Rym: The other thing going on with larger player counts, and again, this is all informal patterns, not formal patterns.

1031
01:08:34,073 --> 01:08:35,617
Rym: They're not hard distinctions.

1032
01:08:37,500 --> 01:08:40,207
Rym: Is that the more players there are, the more likely it is.

1033
01:08:40,247 --> 01:08:44,840
Rym: there is a broader gradient of player skill, which leads to dynamics.

1034
01:08:44,939 --> 01:08:53,120
Rym: Like, in a three-player game, it's unlikely that I will be able to, like, farm the actions of the worst player to better myself in a meaningful way.

1035
01:08:53,560 --> 01:08:57,048
Rym: But if there's 100 players, there's probably 10 bad players.

1036
01:08:57,689 --> 01:09:01,399
Rym: I can go, like, in a deathmatch with 100 players, like a Quake deathmatch that somehow has 100 players.

1037
01:09:02,899 --> 01:09:14,640
Rym: My skill, the skill in a deathmatch with 100 players, like Quake 1, would be to find bad players and kill them as quickly as possible, and just let good players kill you so you can get back to killing bad players.

1038
01:09:15,103 --> 01:09:16,654
Rym: Like, dynamics can be different.

1039
01:09:16,674 --> 01:09:17,439
Scott: Local equilibrium can happen.

1040
01:09:17,439 --> 01:09:20,386
Scott: A lot of that depends on the specific rules of the game, right?

1041
01:09:20,426 --> 01:09:24,256
Scott: Something like PUBG, where when you kill someone, you get their stuff, right?

1042
01:09:24,277 --> 01:09:25,660
Scott: That matters a lot, right?

1043
01:09:26,060 --> 01:09:30,529
Scott: Something like Quake, where you instantly respawn, so dying is not that big a deal, right?

1044
01:09:30,831 --> 01:09:34,720
Scott: Chasing someone for a minute and not getting any frags would be worse than just dying.

1045
01:09:34,760 --> 01:09:35,568
Rym: But here's what I'd say.

1046
01:09:35,890 --> 01:09:49,979
Scott: Small player counts-- But another game where you can't really farm people so much, where there's no benefit to attacking weak players, that doesn't give you a benefit for that, well, then that goes away.

1047
01:09:50,220 --> 01:09:50,421
Rym: Yep.

1048
01:09:50,640 --> 01:09:51,423
Rym: So think of it this way.

1049
01:09:51,783 --> 01:10:00,020
Rym: Small player counts, generally, the actual specifics of the game don't matter that much.

1050
01:10:00,120 --> 01:10:05,480
Rym: That pattern we talked about comes through almost no matter what the mechanics are in a 3-player game.

1051
01:10:05,820 --> 01:10:16,920
Rym: But in a 10-player game versus a 20-player game, there's more nuanced or complex patterns that can emerge that rely more heavily on the specifics of those individual games.

1052
01:10:17,201 --> 01:10:21,520
Rym: It's a lot harder to generalize about play patterns with higher player counts.

1053
01:10:23,840 --> 01:10:33,640
Rym: And we've already gone over an hour, so there's no way we can even begin to talk about player counts in non-Ortho games, which I think there is a topic there, but that's another hour.

1054
01:10:33,780 --> 01:10:41,757
Scott: The point is, stop complaining or saying wrong things when it comes to, "Oh, this game has a 1-player version, 2-player version, 3-player

1055
01:10:41,778 --> 01:10:42,038
Scott: version.".

1056
01:10:42,920 --> 01:10:44,279
Rym: Those are three different games.

1057
01:10:44,620 --> 01:10:52,220
Scott: That those are three different games, and that there are inherent properties of those games that you have to accept, whether you like them or not.

1058
01:10:52,661 --> 01:10:59,419
Scott: So if you don't like them, recognize that and just don't play them instead of saying something wrong like, "I don't like root because it's

1059
01:10:59,479 --> 01:10:59,960
Scott: politics.".

1060
01:10:59,980 --> 01:11:02,431
Scott: It's like, yeah, don't play root.

1061
01:11:02,571 --> 01:11:04,500
Rym: Go play chess or Eitan or something.

1062
01:11:05,223 --> 01:11:06,578
Scott: Yeah, just don't play that then.

1063
01:11:08,822 --> 01:11:10,495
Scott: Don't come ask, "How do I play root

1064
01:11:10,616 --> 01:11:10,979
Scott: solo?".

1065
01:11:11,100 --> 01:11:19,620
Scott: It's like, I'm sure you could take some of the rules of root and make a puzzle out of them, but that's not playing root.

1066
01:11:19,760 --> 01:11:20,959
Scott: Playing root is a political activity.

1067
01:11:21,482 --> 01:11:21,548
Rym: Yep.

1068
01:11:22,344 --> 01:11:23,359
